{
  "texts": [
    "While the FDA has begun to adapt its regulatory framework to address AI technology as medical devices it must move from discussion to action, and provide specific guidance for LLMs 13, 14.",
    "The FDA can learn from the strengths as well as the criticisms of the EU's AI Act, one of the first formal regulations for generative AI 15.",
    "Finally, as with any other healthcare technology, payer incentives must be present before widespread implementation.",
    "Generative AI tools will likely be considered a capital expense in the books of most providers and can follow along the same or similar financing path as EHR systems.",
    "Additionally, given that the cost to create and evaluate generative AI tools remains somewhat prohibitive, both private and public investment will be required to truly push the field forward."
  ]
}